<div1 type="trialAccount" id="t18420822-2541">
               <interp inst="t18420822-2541" type="uri" value="sessionsPapers/18420822"></interp>
               <interp inst="t18420822-2541" type="date" value="18420822"></interp>
               <join result="criminalCharge" id="t18420822-2541-charge-1" targOrder="Y" targets="def1-2541-18420822 t18420822-2541-offence-1 t18420822-2541-verdict-1"></join>
               <p>2541. <persName id="def1-2541-18420822" type="defendantName">
                     <interp inst="def1-2541-18420822" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                     <interp inst="def1-2541-18420822" type="age" value="26"></interp>
                     <interp inst="def1-2541-18420822" type="surname" value="HUGHES"></interp>
                     <interp inst="def1-2541-18420822" type="given" value="JOSEPH"></interp>
                     <hi rend="largeCaps">JOSEPH HUGHES</hi>
                  </persName> was indicted<rs id="t18420822-2541-offence-1" type="offenceDescription">
                     <interp inst="t18420822-2541-offence-1" type="offenceCategory" value="deception"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18420822-2541-offence-1" type="offenceSubcategory" value="forgery"></interp> for feloniously uttering a forged receipt for 12<hi rend="italic">l</hi>., knowing it to be forged, with intent to defraud <persName id="t18420822-name-1806" type="victimName">
                        <interp inst="t18420822-name-1806" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18420822-name-1806" type="surname" value="BURROWS"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18420822-name-1806" type="given" value="SAMUEL"></interp>
                        <join result="offenceVictim" targOrder="Y" targets="t18420822-2541-offence-1 t18420822-name-1806"></join>Samuel Burrows</persName>.</rs>
               </p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">MR. PAYNE</hi> 
                  <hi rend="italic">conducted the Prosecution</hi>.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18420822-name-1807" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18420822-name-1807" type="gender" value="female"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18420822-name-1807" type="surname" value="BURROWS"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18420822-name-1807" type="given" value="MARGARET"></interp>MARGARET BURROWS</persName>
                  </hi>. I am the wife of Samuel Burrows, who is now at sea. On the 8th of February I took a coffee-house of the prisoner, called The Arundel, at Greenwich—I agreed to pay 35<hi rend="italic">l</hi>. a year—he was to be my lodger, and to occupy one bed-room, at 3<hi rend="italic">s</hi>. a week, and to pay extra for what meals he had there—on the 3rd of May he made out this account, and delivered it to me—I think it she as 5<hi rend="italic">l</hi>. 3<hi rend="italic">s</hi>. 10<hi rend="italic">d</hi>. owing to me—on the 8th of May a quarter's rent would become due, which was 8<hi rend="italic">l</hi>. 15<hi rend="italic">s</hi>., and on the 4th of July, a person was put into possession for it—on the 9th of July I signed an agreement to let it remain for three weeks—I have not got that agreement, I believe one of the condemning brokers has it—I do not know whether he is here—on the 3rd of August my demand against the prisoner was 14<hi rend="italic">l</hi>. 5<hi rend="italic">s</hi>. 3<hi rend="italic">d</hi>.—on the 6th of August I</p>
               <xptr type="pageFacsimile" doc="184208220258"></xptr>
               <p>still owed him 8<hi rend="italic">l</hi>. 15<hi rend="italic">s</hi>. for a quarter's rent—there would be another quarter die pm the 8th pf August—on Saturday, the 6th of August, I met the prisoner at the office of Mr. Smith, a solicitor, at Green which, by appointment, for the purpose of settling the accounts between us, and whatever rent was due to him, I was willing and prepared to pay him by the Monday—14<hi rend="italic">l</hi>. 15<hi rend="italic">s</hi>. 3<hi rend="italic">d</hi>. was due to me, and two quarters' rent to him—I should have had to pay him 2<hi rend="italic">l</hi>. 14<hi rend="italic">s</hi>. 9<hi rend="italic">d</hi>.—when I met him at Mr. Smith's he produced this receipt for 12<hi rend="italic">l</hi>., purporting to bear my signature—I had never signed it, nor ever saw it or knew of it till then—I never borrowed 12<hi rend="italic">l</hi>. of the prisoner, nor ever had a fraction in the shape of money from him—he said it was for 12<hi rend="italic">l</hi>. which he had paid me—a man named Tuck was produced for the prisoner before the Magistrate, as a witness to the money being paid—I think he was sworn.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="italic">Cross-examined by</hi> 
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">MR. DOANE</hi>. <hi rend="italic">Q.</hi> The prisoner was obliged to put in a distress on the 3rd of July? <hi rend="italic">A.</hi> Because he did not pay his ac<lb></lb>counts—he put a distress in, and took it off on my promising to pay—I did not pay at that time—I have not had a great many disagreements with people about payments—I cannot tell How many—I do not know whether Mr. Smith is here—I have not brought him here—the first bro<lb></lb>ker employer when this distress was put in was Mr. Parker—I did not see Mr. Dunford on that occasion—since the second distress I did—at that time the prisoner owed me nearly 15<hi rend="italic">l</hi>.—I have the account here—I told Mr. Dunford that—that I swear—the second distress was made on the 9th of August—Mr. Dunford was there when the first distress was made—he was one of the condemning brokers—Parker was the distrain<lb></lb>ing broker—I did not see Mr. Dunford on the second occasion, nor on any other occasion than the one I have spoken of—a man named Maberley was the broker on the second occasion—I never charged other people with forging receipts—that I swear—I know Mary Andrews and her husband signed it or not I do not know, and therefore I could not charge him with it—I never threatened to charge him with forging a receipt—that I swear—I never threatened to charge him with forging my name to a receipt of 3<hi rend="italic">l</hi>. at the Custom-house—there was a book produced which was receipted, but I never charged him with doing it—I never charged or threatened to charge him with forging my name—I never gave him a receipt in pencil for that 3<hi rend="italic">l</hi>.—I cannot tell How often I have been at the Police-office at Greenwich—it might be often—I have gone when I have had occasion to go—I cannot tell you How often—I cannot tell whether I have been there twenty times, thirty times, or forty times—I do not know at all—I cannot tell whether I have not been forty times before the Justice, making charges against individuals—I will not swear that I have not made forty charges against forty different individuals there—I charged a man once with not paying for refreshments which he had at my house—he said he had paid me, but he had not—I charged him with an assault, but it originated in my not being paid—I was on that occasion charged with kicking a man in a certain place—I was not fined—I had to pay 10<hi rend="italic">s</hi>.—I do not know whe<lb></lb>ther I was fined, or whether it was the expenses—I preferred an indict<lb></lb>ment against a man for perjury, after being before the Justice—the bill was not thrown out—I did not come into the witness box—the man was never tried—I never said to Mr. Dunford since I preferred this charge, that for 10<hi rend="italic">l</hi>. I would <hi rend="italic">squash</hi> this indictment, nor that I would make a</p>
               <xptr type="pageFacsimile" doc="184208220259"></xptr>
               <p>flaw in it—I never said, "If Hughes will give up the note, and pay me the difference I won't hurt him"—nor if I had 10<hi rend="italic">l</hi>. from him I would go into the country and <hi rend="italic">squash</hi> the concern—I never said so to any body—I did not say, "You know, Mr. Dunford, a word before the Grand Jury will do it"—I did not after the prisoner was in charge go to Sergeant Good and tell him I suspected he had committed a murder—I did not tell him there was a smell in the room, and I believed a murder had been committed there—I did not say so to Arthur—I said, there was a very offensive smell in the room, something I could not possibly make out, and re<lb></lb>quested their interference—I said it was certainly like a dead body, or something of that kind—it was a very unnatural smell—I never said to Good, or Arthur that I believed there was a murdered man in the pri<lb></lb>soner's room—I remember seeing Good and Arthur when I was in com<lb></lb>pany with the witness Weale—Arthur did not on that occasion tax me with having taken a false oath before the Magistrate—I did not say I had done so to save myself the trouble I had got into, that I had got into trouble enough about this business already, and I did not want any more—I never alluded to a false oath—nothing of the sort occurred.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">MR. PATNE</hi>. <hi rend="italic">Q.</hi> Have you ever on any occasion, when you have gone before a Magistrate, made a false or incorrect charge? <hi rend="italic">A.</hi> Not that I know of—I have always strictly stated the truth—I have not kept an account of the number of times, I have had occasion to take people be<lb></lb>fore a Magistrate, or to go before a Magistrate—I should say I have not been forty times before a Magistrate.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18420822-name-1808" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18420822-name-1808" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18420822-name-1808" type="surname" value="HEALEY"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18420822-name-1808" type="given" value="JOHN"></interp>JOHN HEALEY</persName>
                  </hi>. I am a solicitor, and live in Keppel-street, Black<lb></lb>friars-road—I have known Mrs. Burrows rather more than eleven years, and am very well acquainted with her hand-writing—I have seen this re<lb></lb>ceipt before, at Mr. Smith's office, and before the Magistrate—the words "<hi rend="italic">Mergret</hi> Burrows," and the name above that, is certainly not in her handwriting—the body of it the prisoner says be wrote himself—the name if Dot at all like her writing—she cannot write so well—I never saw any so good.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="italic">Cross-examined by</hi> 
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">MR. PHILLIPS</hi>. <hi rend="italic">Q.</hi> Why, is that not very bad? <hi rend="italic">A.</hi> It is not good—I have seen a good deal worse—I am not practising as an attorney for myself, and have not for the last sixteen years—I have not taken out my certificate—I have been acting at clerk in other offices, but I am a solicitor—I last saw Mrs. Burrows write about a week or ten days ago, and I had seen her write a day or two before the charge was made before the Magistrate—she has consulted me on every occasion where, she has been in trouble since her husband went away—in the early part of the time I was acquainted with her she consulted me as regarded her property, previous to her marriage, and subsequently she has consulted me very often indeed, with regard to this business at Greenwich, I mean the business between her and the prisoner—not about this note—I was not her attorney in the assault cases—I never went to the police-court at Greenwich on her account—she consulted me upon that, and I advised her to go to Mr. May, and take him with her—I have never been there with her—I am not the attorney for this prosecution.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18420822-name-1809" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18420822-name-1809" type="gender" value="female"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18420822-name-1809" type="surname" value="WEALE"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18420822-name-1809" type="given" value="ELIZA"></interp>ELIZA WEALE</persName>
                  </hi>. I have lived for several months with Mrs. Burrows, as<lb></lb>sisting her in her business at Greenwich, since last Easter. On the 4th of July, a distress was put into the house for rent, and a second distress was put in this month—on the first occasion I heard her say to the prisoner "It</p>
               <xptr type="pageFacsimile" doc="184208220260"></xptr>
               <p>is very hard that you should distrain on me for rent, knowing that you owe me more for board and lodging"—he said, "I will have my rent, you may get what I owe you in the best way you can"—I never heard him men<lb></lb>tion a sum of 12<hi rend="italic">l</hi>. that he had lent or paid her, or anything of the kind.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="italic">Cross-examined by</hi> 
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">MR. DOANE</hi>. <hi rend="italic">Q.</hi> Were they not quarrelling? <hi rend="italic">A.</hi> Yes—it was on the Saturday before the first distress—I heard Mrs. Burrows ask the prisoner to come to terms on the Monday that the distraint was put in, and several times.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">MR. PAYNE</hi>. <hi rend="italic">Q.</hi> The conversation took place on the Monday, and the quarrel on the Saturday? <hi rend="italic">A.</hi> Yes.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18420822-name-1810" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18420822-name-1810" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18420822-name-1810" type="surname" value="GOOD"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18420822-name-1810" type="given" value="GEORGE"></interp>GEORGE GOOD</persName>
                  </hi> (<hi rend="italic">police-sergeant R</hi> 2.) The prisoner was given into my custody by Mrs. Burrows, at the coffee-shop, on Tuesday, the 9th of Au<lb></lb>gust, for forging a receipt—I asked him to produce the receipt, that I might show it to her—he refused to do so—he went up stairs—I followed him, and Mrs. Burrows came immediately after me—I did not see her till I got into the room—I went in after the prisoner—I asked him to let me see the receipt, so that Mrs. Burrows might see it—he said he was advised not to show it, and would not show it any more—I had seen it before—he afterwards pulled it out, and laid it on the table—while it was on the table, Mrs. Burrows came in—she said that it was a forgery, it was not hers, she had never seen it before till she had seen it at Mr. Smith's office—the prisoner took it off the table and put it into his pocket—I took him into custody, found the receipt on him, took possession of it, and have produced it to-day—the prisoner called a man named Tuck, as a witness, before the Magistrate.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="italic">Cross-examined by</hi> 
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">MR. DOANE</hi>. <hi rend="italic">Q.</hi> He did not object to show you the receipt? <hi rend="italic">A.</hi> He did at first—he would not show it to me before Mrs. Burrows, but I had seen it before—he showed it to me, with the broker, when Mrs. Burrows was not present—I remember being in company with Mrs. Burrows and the witness Weale, in the presence of Arthur, a police-constable, a day or two after I had taken the prisoner—we were in a room in Mrs. Burrows' coffee-house—Arthur said that she had taken a false oath before the Magistrate, and she said she believed she had—that was allud<lb></lb>ing to Eliza Weale—I do not remember her saving she had done so to save herself trouble, that she had got into trouble enough already—that might have been said—she said she believed she had taken a false oath—I remember the prosecutrix telling me, after the prisoner was given into cus<lb></lb>tody, that she suspected there was a murdered man in the prisoner's room—she came to the station, and said there was a dreadful stench in the room which the prisoner occupied, and she believed there was something there which should not be, that it smelt as if some dead body was in the room.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">MR. PAYNE</hi>. <hi rend="italic">Q.</hi> Who was present when this matter about the false oath took place? <hi rend="italic">A.</hi> Mrs. Burrows, Mr. Dunford, Arthur, and myself and Mr. Davis—it was at the time I went to see what caused the stench—I believe Mrs. Burrows and Arthur began the conversation—I cannot tell what was first said—I did not take particular notice what it was all about—it was respecting some woman she had had taken up a day or two be<lb></lb>fore—I believe the false oath was in reference to that woman—Arthur said he thought that Eliza Weale had taken a false oath, not that Mrs. Burrows had—that is what I mean, and that was what I said before—Arthur said to Mrs. Burrows that Eliza Weale had taken a false oath be<lb></lb>fore</p>
               <xptr type="pageFacsimile" doc="184208220261"></xptr>
               <p>the Magistrate—I did not understand him to say that Mrs. Burrows had—Arthur is here.</p>
               <p>(<hi rend="italic">Receipt read</hi>)—"Received, July 2, 1842, from Mr. Joseph Hughes, the sum of 12<hi rend="italic">l</hi>. for board and lodging, from Feb. 8, 1842, to Aug. 9, 1842, which sum pays for lodging and board only to that time, Aug. 9, 1842, and all meals had between the date of this receipt and the said Aug. 9th to be paid for on delivery, which J. A. agrees to. My husband, Samuel Burrows, being at sea, has authorised me, <hi rend="italic">Mergrat</hi> Burrows, to pay and receive his accounts; and I further agree to pay Mr. Joseph Hughes 18<hi rend="italic">d</hi>. per week for the loan of a bedstead, bed, wool palliasse, pillows and appertenances, from April 5, 1842.—<hi rend="italic">Mergrat</hi> Burrows, as per receipt above, for board and lodging, 12<hi rend="italic">l</hi>.—<hi rend="italic">Mergrat</hi> Bur"—(<hi rend="italic">the remainder of the name was torn or burnt off</hi>.)</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">MRS. BURROWS</hi> 
                  <hi rend="italic">re-examined</hi>. I always spell my name <hi rend="italic">Margaret</hi>—I never signed my name at the bottom of a blank piece of paper with a stamp on it—I never signed my name to any paper for the prisoner, the corner of which was burnt off, and then signed it again—I never gave him a receipt of any kind—I never received 12<hi rend="italic">l</hi>. from him, nor any money whatever, not a farthing.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">MR. PHILLIPS</hi> 
                  <hi rend="italic">called</hi>
               </p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18420822-name-1811" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18420822-name-1811" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18420822-name-1811" type="surname" value="DUNFORD"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18420822-name-1811" type="given" value="HENRY"></interp>HENRY DUNFORD</persName>
                  </hi>. I am an auctioneer and house-agent, and live at Greenwich. I know the prosecutrix from a very slight acquaintance since the 9th of July—I was employed in the first distress at that time, as the appraiser—about the 10th or 11th of this month I saw her at her own house—she said to me, "If Hughes will give up the receipt and pay me the difference, I won't hurt him; if Hughes behaves well to me, and I have 10<hi rend="italic">l</hi>., I will go into the country and <hi rend="italic">squash</hi> the concern"—I cannot say that she said, "You know, Mr. Dunford, a word before the Grand Jury will do it"—this was at the second distress—she never told me that the prisoner owed her 12<hi rend="italic">l</hi>.—I was present when the agreement was made to redeem the goods—that was the time this occurred.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">MR. PAYNE</hi>. <hi rend="italic">Q.</hi> When was this conversation between you and Mrs. Bur<lb></lb>rows? <hi rend="italic">A.</hi> On the 9th, 10th, or 11th of August—I did not take particular notice—I had occasion to go there—I had a conversation with her respect<lb></lb>ing the moving a sippy-table, and in the conversation this came out.</p>
               <p>(<hi rend="italic">The Jury, on examining the date on the stamp, stated it to be</hi> 18—7, <hi rend="italic">meaning the</hi> 18<hi rend="italic">th of</hi> 7 <hi rend="italic">th mouth, July, which was subsequent to the date of the receipt</hi>.)</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="largeCaps">
                     <rs id="t18420822-2541-verdict-1" type="verdictDescription">
                        <interp inst="t18420822-2541-verdict-1" type="verdictCategory" value="guilty"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18420822-2541-verdict-1" type="verdictSubcategory" value="no_subcategory"></interp>GUILTY</rs>
                  </hi>. Aged 26.—
<rs id="t18420822-2541-punishment-322" type="punishmentDescription">
                     <interp inst="t18420822-2541-punishment-322" type="punishmentCategory" value="imprison"></interp>
